# TypeScript And Performance Rule

- Write new code in TypeScript.
- In Excalidraw core rendering/canvas hot paths, avoid allocating new objects/arrays inside frame loops; reuse existing buffers/maps and hoist reusable temporaries outside the loop.
- In scene/element update flows, treat shared element collections as immutable (`readonly` inputs, `const` references, copy-on-write when needed) and do not mutate shared arrays in place.
- In collaboration/networking and input processing code, prefer `?.` and `??` for partial payloads/events and avoid verbose guard ladders that obscure fast-path logic.
- Avoid heavy abstractions in draw/update hot paths (deep wrapper chains, per-element closures, unnecessary object reshaping); prefer direct loops and simple data access patterns.

## How to verify

- Confirm changed source files are TypeScript (`.ts` or `.tsx`).
- Confirm rendering/update loops do not allocate per-iteration helper objects/arrays when a reusable buffer would work.
- Confirm element list handling uses `const`/`readonly` semantics and does not mutate shared scene arrays in place.
- Confirm collaboration/input parsing uses `?.` and `??` for nullable fields/events.
- Confirm draw/update hot paths do not introduce heavy abstractions that add avoidable CPU overhead.
